[src:closest-pair-algorithm/closest-pair-of-points-problem] The **closest pair of points problem** or **closest pair problem** is a problem of computational geometry: given n points in metric space, find a pair of points with the smallest distance between them.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/closest-pair-of-points-problem] The closest pair problem for points in the Euclidean plane was among the first geometric problems that were treated at the origins of the systematic study of the computational complexity of geometric algorithms.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/closest-pair-of-points-problem] Randomized algorithms that solve the problem in linear time are known, in Euclidean spaces whose dimension is treated as a constant for the purposes of asymptotic analysis.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/closest-pair-of-points-problem] This is significantly faster than the $O(n^{2})$ time (expressed here in big O notation) that would be obtained by a naive algorithm of finding distances between all pairs of points and selecting the smallest.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/closest-pair-of-points-problem] It is also possible to solve the problem without randomization, in random-access machine models of computation with unlimited memory that allow the use of the floor function, in near-linear $O(n\log \log n)$ time.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/closest-pair-of-points-problem] In even more restricted models of computation, such as the algebraic decision tree, the problem can be solved in the somewhat slower $O(n\log n)$ time bound, and this is optimal for this model, by a reduction from the element uniqueness problem.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/closest-pair-of-points-problem] Both sweep line algorithms and divide-and-conquer algorithms with this slower time bound are commonly taught as examples of these algorithm design techniques.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/closest-pair-of-points-problem] Round the input points to a square grid of points whose size (the separation between adjacent grid points) is d , and use a hash table to collect together pairs of input points that round to the same grid point.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/closest-pair-of-points-problem] For each input point, compute the distance to all other inputs that either round to the same grid point or to another grid point within the Moore neighborhood of $3^{k}-1$ surrounding grid points.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/closest-pair-of-points-problem] Return the smallest of the distances computed throughout this process.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/closest-pair-of-points-problem] The algorithm will always correctly determine the closest pair, because it maps any pair closer than distance d to the same grid point or to adjacent grid points.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/closest-pair-of-points-problem] The uniform sampling of pairs in the first step of the algorithm (compared to a different method of Rabin for sampling a similar number of pairs) simplifies the proof that the expected number of distances computed by the algorithm is linear.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/closest-pair-of-points-problem] Compute the distances from p to all the other points of S and let d be the minimum such distance.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/closest-pair-of-points-problem] Round the input points to a square grid of size $d/(2{\sqrt {k}})$ , and delete from S all points whose Moore neighborhood has no other points.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/closest-pair-of-points-problem] The approximate distance found by this filtering process is the final value of d , computed in the step before S becomes empty.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/closest-pair-of-points-problem] Each step removes all points whose closest neighbor is at distance d or greater, at least half of the points in expectation, from which it follows that the total expected time for filtering is linear.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/closest-pair-of-points-problem] Once an approximate value of d is known, it can be used for the final steps of Rabin's algorithm; in these steps each grid point has a constant number of inputs rounded to it, so again the time is linear.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/closest-pair-of-points-problem] If the bounding box for all points is known in advance and the constant-time floor function is available, then the expected $O(n)$ -space data structure was suggested that supports expected-time $O(\log n)$ insertions and deletions and constant query time.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/closest-pair-of-points-problem] When modified for the algebraic decision tree model, insertions and deletions would require $O(\log ^{2}n)$ expected time.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/closest-pair-of-points-problem] The complexity of the dynamic closest pair algorithm cited above is exponential in the dimension d , and therefore such an algorithm becomes less suitable for high-dimensional problems.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/closest-pair-of-points-problem] An algorithm for the dynamic closest-pair problem in d dimensional space was developed by Sergey Bespamyatnikh in 1998.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/closest-pair-of-points-problem] Points can be inserted and deleted in $O(\log n)$ time per point (in the worst case).
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/delaunay-triangulation] This maximizes the size of the smallest angle in any of the triangles, and tends to avoid sliver triangles.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/delaunay-triangulation] The triangulation is named after Boris Delaunay for his work on it from 1934.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/delaunay-triangulation] If the points all lie on a straight line, the notion of triangulation becomes degenerate and there is no Delaunay triangulation.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/delaunay-triangulation] By considering circumscribed spheres, the notion of Delaunay triangulation extends to three and higher dimensions.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/delaunay-triangulation] Generalizations are possible to metrics other than Euclidean distance.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/delaunay-triangulation] However, in these cases a Delaunay triangulation is not guaranteed to exist or be unique.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/delaunay-triangulation] The Delaunay triangulation with all the circumcircles and their centers (in red).
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/delaunay-triangulation] The Delaunay triangulation of a discrete point set **P** in general position corresponds to the dual graph of the Voronoi diagram for **P**.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/delaunay-triangulation] The circumcenters of Delaunay triangles are the vertices of the Voronoi diagram.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/delaunay-triangulation] In the 2D case, the Voronoi vertices are connected via edges, that can be derived from adjacency-relationships of the Delaunay triangles: If two triangles share an edge in the Delaunay triangulation, their circumcenters are to be connected with an edge in the Voronoi tesselation.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/delaunay-triangulation] For a set **P** of points in the (d-dimensional) Euclidean space, a **Delaunay triangulation** is a triangulation DT(**P**) such that no point in **P** is inside the circum-hypersphere of any d-simplex in DT(**P**).
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/delaunay-triangulation] It is known that there exists a unique Delaunay triangulation for **P** if **P** is a set of points in *general position*; that is, the affine hull of **P** is d-dimensional and no set of *d* + 2 points in **P** lie on the boundary of a ball whose interior does not intersect **P**.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/delaunay-triangulation] The problem of finding the Delaunay triangulation of a set of points in d-dimensional Euclidean space can be converted to the problem of finding the convex hull of a set of points in (*d* + 1)-dimensional space.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/delaunay-triangulation] As the convex hull is unique, so is the triangulation, assuming all facets of the convex hull are simplices.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/delaunay-triangulation] Nonsimplicial facets only occur when *d* + 2 of the original points lie on the same d-hypersphere, i.e., the points are not in general position.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/delaunay-triangulation] Let n be the number of points and d the number of dimensions.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/delaunay-triangulation] From the above properties an important feature arises: Looking at two triangles △*ABD*, △*BCD* with the common edge BD (see figures), if the sum of the angles α + γ ≤ 180°, the triangles meet the Delaunay condition.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/delaunay-triangulation] This is an important property because it allows the use of a *flipping* technique.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/delaunay-triangulation] This operation is called a *flip*, and can be generalised to three and higher dimensions.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/delaunay-triangulation] Many algorithms for computing Delaunay triangulations rely on fast operations for detecting when a point is within a triangle's circumcircle and an efficient data structure for storing triangles and edges.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/delaunay-triangulation] When A, B, C are sorted in a counterclockwise order, this determinant is positive only if D lies inside the circumcircle.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/delaunay-triangulation] As mentioned above, if a triangle is non-Delaunay, we can flip one of its edges.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/delaunay-triangulation] This leads to a straightforward algorithm: construct any triangulation of the points, and then flip edges until no triangle is non-Delaunay.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/delaunay-triangulation] Unfortunately, this can take Ω(*n*2) edge flips.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/delaunay-triangulation] While this algorithm can be generalised to three and higher dimensions, its convergence is not guaranteed in these cases, as it is conditioned to the connectedness of the underlying flip graph: this graph is connected for two-dimensional sets of points, but may be disconnected in higher dimensions.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/delaunay-triangulation] The most straightforward way of efficiently computing the Delaunay triangulation is to repeatedly add one vertex at a time, retriangulating the affected parts of the graph.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/delaunay-triangulation] When a vertex v is added, we split in three the triangle that contains v, then we apply the flip algorithm.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/delaunay-triangulation] Done naïvely, this will take O(*n*) time: we search through all the triangles to find the one that contains v, then we potentially flip away every triangle.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/delaunay-triangulation] If we insert vertices in random order, it turns out (by a somewhat intricate proof) that each insertion will flip, on average, only O(1) triangles – although sometimes it will flip many more.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/delaunay-triangulation] This still leaves the point location time to improve.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/delaunay-triangulation] We can store the history of the splits and flips performed: each triangle stores a pointer to the two or three triangles that replaced it.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/delaunay-triangulation] To find the triangle that contains v, we start at a root triangle, and follow the pointer that points to a triangle that contains v, until we find a triangle that has not yet been replaced.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/delaunay-triangulation] On average, this will also take O(log *n*) time.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/delaunay-triangulation] Over all vertices, then, this takes O(*n* log *n*) time.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/delaunay-triangulation] While the technique extends to higher dimensions (as proved by Edelsbrunner and Shah), the runtime can be exponential in the dimension even if the final Delaunay triangulation is small.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/delaunay-triangulation] The Bowyer–Watson algorithm provides another approach for incremental construction.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/delaunay-triangulation] It gives an alternative to edge flipping for computing the Delaunay triangles containing a newly inserted vertex.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/delaunay-triangulation] Unfortunately the flipping-based algorithms are generally hard to parallelize, since adding some certain point (e.g. the center point of a wagon wheel) can lead to up to O(*n*) consecutive flips.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/delaunay-triangulation] Blelloch et al. proposed another version of incremental algorithm based on rip-and-tent, which is practical and highly parallelized with polylogarithmic span.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/delaunay-triangulation] A divide and conquer algorithm for triangulations in two dimensions was developed by Lee and Schachter and improved by Guibas and Stolfi and later by Dwyer.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/delaunay-triangulation] In this algorithm, one recursively draws a line to split the vertices into two sets.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/delaunay-triangulation] The Delaunay triangulation is computed for each set, and then the two sets are merged along the splitting line.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/delaunay-triangulation] Using some clever tricks, the merge operation can be done in time O(*n*), so the total running time is O(*n* log *n*).
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/delaunay-triangulation] For certain types of point sets, such as a uniform random distribution, by intelligently picking the splitting lines the expected time can be reduced to O(*n* log log *n*) while still maintaining worst-case performance.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/delaunay-triangulation] A divide and conquer paradigm to performing a triangulation in d dimensions is presented in "DeWall: A fast divide and conquer Delaunay triangulation algorithm in E*d*" by P.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/delaunay-triangulation] The divide and conquer algorithm has been shown to be the fastest DT generation technique sequentially.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/delaunay-triangulation] Sweephull is a hybrid technique for 2D Delaunay triangulation that uses a radially propagating sweep-hull, and a flipping algorithm.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/delaunay-triangulation] The sweep-hull is created sequentially by iterating a radially-sorted set of 2D points, and connecting triangles to the visible part of the convex hull, which gives a non-overlapping triangulation.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/delaunay-triangulation] One can build a convex hull in this manner so long as the order of points guarantees no point would fall within the triangle.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/delaunay-triangulation] But, radially sorting should minimize flipping by being highly Delaunay to start.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/delaunay-triangulation] This is then paired with a final iterative triangle flipping step.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/delaunay-triangulation] The Euclidean minimum spanning tree of a set of points is a subset of the Delaunay triangulation of the same points, and this can be exploited to compute it efficiently.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/delaunay-triangulation] For modelling terrain or other objects given a point cloud, the Delaunay triangulation gives a nice set of triangles to use as polygons in the model.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/delaunay-triangulation] In particular, the Delaunay triangulation avoids narrow triangles (as they have large circumcircles compared to their area).
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/delaunay-triangulation] Delaunay triangulations can be used to determine the density or intensity of points samplings by means of the Delaunay tessellation field estimator (DTFE).
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/delaunay-triangulation] Delaunay triangulations are often used to generate meshes for space-discretised solvers such as the finite element method and the finite volume method of physics simulation, because of the angle guarantee and because fast triangulation algorithms have been developed.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/delaunay-triangulation] Typically, the domain to be meshed is specified as a coarse simplicial complex; for the mesh to be numerically stable, it must be refined, for instance by using Ruppert's algorithm.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/delaunay-triangulation] The increasing popularity of finite element method and boundary element method techniques increases the incentive to improve automatic meshing algorithms.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/delaunay-triangulation] However, all of these algorithms can create distorted and even unusable grid elements.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/delaunay-triangulation] Fortunately, several techniques exist which can take an existing mesh and improve its quality.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/delaunay-triangulation] For example, smoothing (also referred to as mesh refinement) is one such method, which repositions nodes to minimize element distortion.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/delaunay-triangulation] The stretched grid method allows the generation of pseudo-regular meshes that meet the Delaunay criteria easily and quickly in a one-step solution.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/delaunay-triangulation] Constrained Delaunay triangulation has found applications in path planning in automated driving and topographic surveying.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] In computer science, **divide and conquer** is an algorithm design paradigm.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] A divide-and-conquer algorithm recursively breaks down a problem into two or more sub-problems of the same or related type, until these become simple enough to be solved directly.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] The solutions to the sub-problems are then combined to give a solution to the original problem.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] Designing efficient divide-and-conquer algorithms can be difficult.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] As in mathematical induction, it is often necessary to generalize the problem to make it amenable to a recursive solution.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] The correctness of a divide-and-conquer algorithm is usually proved by mathematical induction, and its computational cost is often determined by solving recurrence relations.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] The divide-and-conquer paradigm is often used to find an optimal solution of a problem.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] Its basic idea is to decompose a given problem into two or more similar, but simpler, subproblems, to solve them in turn, and to compose their solutions to solve the given problem.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] Problems of sufficient simplicity are solved directly.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] For example, to sort a given list of *n* natural numbers, split it into two lists of about *n*/2 numbers each, sort each of them in turn, and interleave both results appropriately to obtain the sorted version of the given list (see the picture).
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] This approach is known as the merge sort algorithm.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] The name "divide and conquer" is sometimes applied to algorithms that reduce each problem to only one sub-problem, such as the binary search algorithm for finding a record in a sorted list (or its analogue in numerical computing, the bisection algorithm for root finding).
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] These algorithms can be implemented more efficiently than general divide-and-conquer algorithms; in particular, if they use tail recursion, they can be converted into simple loops.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] Under this broad definition, however, every algorithm that uses recursion or loops could be regarded as a "divide-and-conquer algorithm".
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] Therefore, some authors consider that the name "divide and conquer" should be used only when each problem may generate two or more subproblems.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] The name **decrease and conquer** has been proposed instead for the single-subproblem class.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] Early examples of these algorithms are primarily decrease and conquer – the original problem is successively broken down into *single* subproblems, and indeed can be solved iteratively.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] Binary search, a decrease-and-conquer algorithm where the subproblems are of roughly half the original size, has a long history.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] While a clear description of the algorithm on computers appeared in 1946 in an article by John Mauchly, the idea of using a sorted list of items to facilitate searching dates back at least as far as Babylonia in 200 BC.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] Another ancient decrease-and-conquer algorithm is the Euclidean algorithm to compute the greatest common divisor of two numbers by reducing the numbers to smaller and smaller equivalent subproblems, which dates to several centuries BC.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] An early two-subproblem D&C algorithm that was specifically developed for computers and properly analyzed is the merge sort algorithm, invented by John von Neumann in 1945.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] Another notable example is the algorithm invented by Anatolii A.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] Karatsuba in 1960 that could multiply two *n*-digit numbers in $O(n^{\log _{2}3})$ operations (in Big O notation).
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] This algorithm disproved Andrey Kolmogorov's 1956 conjecture that $\Omega (n^{2})$ operations would be required for that task.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] This is related to a radix sort, described for punch-card sorting machines as early as 1929.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] Divide and conquer is a powerful tool for solving conceptually difficult problems: all it requires is a way of breaking the problem into sub-problems, of solving the trivial cases, and of combining sub-problems to the original problem.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] Similarly, decrease and conquer only requires reducing the problem to a single smaller problem, such as the classic Tower of Hanoi puzzle, which reduces moving a tower of height n to move a tower of height $n-1$ .
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] The divide-and-conquer paradigm often helps in the discovery of efficient algorithms.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] It was the key, for example, to Karatsuba's fast multiplication method, the quicksort and mergesort algorithms, the Strassen algorithm for matrix multiplication, and fast Fourier transforms.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] In all these examples, the D&C approach led to an improvement in the asymptotic cost of the solution.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] For other types of divide-and-conquer approaches, running times can also be generalized.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] If, instead, the work of splitting the problem and combining the partial solutions take $cn^{2}$ time, and there are 2 subproblems where each has size ${\frac {n}{2}}$ , then the running time of the divide-and-conquer algorithm is bounded by $O(n^{2})$ .
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] Divide-and-conquer algorithms are naturally adapted for execution in multi-processor machines, especially shared-memory systems where the communication of data between processors does not need to be planned in advance because distinct sub-problems can be executed on different processors.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] Divide-and-conquer algorithms naturally tend to make efficient use of memory caches.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] The reason is that once a sub-problem is small enough, it and all its sub-problems can, in principle, be solved within the cache, without accessing the slower main memory.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] An algorithm designed to exploit the cache in this way is called *cache-oblivious*, because it does not contain the cache size as an explicit parameter.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] Moreover, D&C algorithms can be designed for important algorithms (e.g., sorting, FFTs, and matrix multiplication) to be *optimal* cache-oblivious algorithms–they use the cache in a probably optimal way, in an asymptotic sense, regardless of the cache size.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] The same advantage exists with regards to other hierarchical storage systems, such as NUMA or virtual memory, as well as for multiple levels of cache: once a sub-problem is small enough, it can be solved within a given level of the hierarchy, without accessing the higher (slower) levels.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] In computations with rounded arithmetic, e.g. with floating-point numbers, a divide-and-conquer algorithm may yield more accurate results than a superficially equivalent iterative method.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] For example, one can add *N* numbers either by a simple loop that adds each datum to a single variable, or by a D&C algorithm called pairwise summation that breaks the data set into two halves, recursively computes the sum of each half, and then adds the two sums.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] While the second method performs the same number of additions as the first and pays the overhead of the recursive calls, it is usually more accurate.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] Divide-and-conquer algorithms are naturally implemented as recursive procedures.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] In that case, the partial sub-problems leading to the one currently being solved are automatically stored in the procedure call stack.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] A recursive function is a function that calls itself within its definition.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] Divide-and-conquer algorithms can also be implemented by a non-recursive program that stores the partial sub-problems in some explicit data structure, such as a stack, queue, or priority queue.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] This approach allows more freedom in the choice of the sub-problem that is to be solved next, a feature that is important in some applications — e.g. in breadth-first recursion and the branch-and-bound method for function optimization.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] This approach is also the standard solution in programming languages that do not provide support for recursive procedures.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] In recursive implementations of D&C algorithms, one must make sure that there is sufficient memory allocated for the recursion stack, otherwise, the execution may fail because of stack overflow.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] D&C algorithms that are time-efficient often have relatively small recursion depth.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] For example, the quicksort algorithm can be implemented so that it never requires more than $\log _{2}n$ nested recursive calls to sort n items.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] Stack overflow can be difficult to prevent when using recursive procedures, since many compilers treat the recursion stack as a contiguous block of memory, and some reserve a fixed amount of space for it.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] In addition, compilers may store more information on the recursion stack than is strictly required, including the return address, unchanged parameters, and the procedure’s local variables.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] As a result, the likelihood of stack overflow may be reduced by limiting the number of parameters and local variables in the recursive procedure, or by replacing recursion with an explicit stack data structure.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] In any recursive algorithm, there is considerable freedom in the choice of the *base cases*, the small subproblems that are solved directly in order to terminate the recursion.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] Choosing the smallest or simplest possible base cases is more elegant and usually leads to simpler programs, because there are fewer cases to consider and they are easier to solve.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] For example, a Fast Fourier Transform algorithm could stop the recursion when the input is a single sample, and the quicksort list-sorting algorithm could stop when the input is the empty list; in both examples, there is only one base case to consider, and it requires no processing.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] On the other hand, efficiency often improves if the recursion is stopped at relatively large base cases, and these are solved non-recursively, resulting in a hybrid algorithm.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] This strategy avoids the overhead of recursive calls that do little or no work and may also allow the use of specialized non-recursive algorithms that, for those base cases, are more efficient than explicit recursion.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] A general procedure for a simple hybrid recursive algorithm is *short-circuiting the base case*, also known as *arm's-length recursion*.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] In this case, whether the next step will result in the base case is checked before the function call, avoiding an unnecessary function call.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] For example, in a tree, rather than recursing to a child node and then checking whether it is null, checking null before recursing avoids half the function calls in some algorithms on binary trees.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] Since a D&C algorithm eventually reduces each problem or sub-problem instance to a large number of base instances, these often dominate the overall cost of the algorithm, especially when the splitting/joining overhead is low.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] Note that these considerations do not depend on whether recursion is implemented by the compiler or by an explicit stack.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] Thus, for example, many library implementations of quicksort will switch to a simple loop-based insertion sort (or similar) algorithm once the number of items to be sorted is sufficiently small.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] Note that, if the empty list were the only base case, sorting a list with n entries would entail maximally n quicksort calls that would do nothing but return immediately.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] Increasing the base cases to lists of size 2 or less will eliminate most of those do-nothing calls, and more generally a base case larger than 2 is typically used to reduce the fraction of time spent in function-call overhead or stack manipulation.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] For example, this approach is used in some efficient FFT implementations, where the base cases are unrolled implementations of divide-and-conquer FFT algorithms for a set of fixed sizes.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] Source-code generation methods may be used to produce the large number of separate base cases desirable to implement this strategy efficiently.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] The generalized version of this idea is known as recursion "unrolling" or "coarsening", and various techniques have been proposed for automating the procedure of enlarging the base case.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] For some problems, the branched recursion may end up evaluating the same sub-problem many times over.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] In such cases it may be worth identifying and saving the solutions to these overlapping subproblems, a technique which is commonly known as memoization.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] Followed to the limit, it leads to bottom-up divide-and-conquer algorithms such as dynamic programming.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/euclidean-distance] In mathematics, the **Euclidean distance** between two points in a Euclidean space is the length of the line segment between them.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/euclidean-distance] It can be calculated from the Cartesian coordinates of the points using the Pythagorean theorem, and therefore is occasionally called the **Pythagorean distance**.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/euclidean-distance] These names come from the ancient Greek mathematicians Euclid and Pythagoras.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/euclidean-distance] In the Greek deductive geometry exemplified by Euclid's *Elements*, distances were not represented as numbers but line segments of the same length, which were considered "equal".
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/euclidean-distance] The notion of distance is inherent in the compass tool used to draw a circle, whose points all have the same distance from a common center point.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/euclidean-distance] The connection from the Pythagorean theorem to distance calculation was not made until the 18th century.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/euclidean-distance] The distance between two objects that are not points is usually defined to be the smallest distance among pairs of points from the two objects.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/euclidean-distance] Formulas are known for computing distances between different types of objects, such as the distance from a point to a line.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/euclidean-distance] In advanced mathematics, the concept of distance has been generalized to abstract metric spaces, and other distances than Euclidean have been studied.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/euclidean-distance] In some applications in statistics and optimization, the square of the Euclidean distance is used instead of the distance itself.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/euclidean-distance] The distance between any two points on the real line is the absolute value of the numerical difference of their coordinates, their absolute difference.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/euclidean-distance] In this formula, squaring and then taking the square root leaves any positive number unchanged, but replaces any negative number by its absolute value.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/euclidean-distance] In the Euclidean plane, let point p have Cartesian coordinates $(p_{1},p_{2})$ and let point q have coordinates $(q_{1},q_{2})$ .
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/euclidean-distance] This can be seen by applying the Pythagorean theorem to a right triangle with horizontal and vertical sides, having the line segment from p to q as its hypotenuse.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/euclidean-distance] The two squared formulas inside the square root give the areas of squares on the horizontal and vertical sides, and the outer square root converts the area of the square on the hypotenuse into the length of the hypotenuse.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/euclidean-distance] It is also possible to compute the distance for points given by polar coordinates.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/euclidean-distance] For pairs of objects that are not both points, the distance can most simply be defined as the smallest distance between any two points from the two objects, although more complicated generalizations from points to sets such as Hausdorff distance are also commonly used.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/euclidean-distance] The distance from a point to a curve can be used to define its parallel curve, another curve all of whose points have the same distance to the given curve.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/euclidean-distance] Another property, Ptolemy's inequality, concerns the Euclidean distances among four points p , q , r , and s .
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/euclidean-distance] For points in the plane, this can be rephrased as stating that for every quadrilateral, the products of opposite sides of the quadrilateral sum to at least as large a number as the product of its diagonals.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/euclidean-distance] However, Ptolemy's inequality applies more generally to points in Euclidean spaces of any dimension, no matter how they are arranged.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/euclidean-distance] For points in metric spaces that are not Euclidean spaces, this inequality may not be true.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/euclidean-distance] Euclidean distance geometry studies properties of Euclidean distance such as Ptolemy's inequality, and their application in testing whether given sets of distances come from points in a Euclidean space.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/euclidean-distance] According to the Beckman–Quarles theorem, any transformation of the Euclidean plane or of a higher-dimensional Euclidean space that preserves unit distances must be an isometry, preserving all distances.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/euclidean-distance] In many applications, and in particular when comparing distances, it may be more convenient to omit the final square root in the calculation of Euclidean distances, as the square root does not change the order ( $d_{1}^{2}>d_{2}^{2}$ if and only if $d_{1}>d_{2}$ ).
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/euclidean-distance] The value resulting from this omission is the square of the Euclidean distance, and is called the **squared Euclidean distance**.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/euclidean-distance] For instance, the Euclidean minimum spanning tree can be determined using only the ordering between distances, and not their numeric values.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/euclidean-distance] Comparing squared distances produces the same result but avoids an unnecessary square-root calculation and sidesteps issues of numerical precision.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/euclidean-distance] The addition of squared distances to each other, as is done in least squares fitting, corresponds to an operation on (unsquared) distances called Pythagorean addition.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/euclidean-distance] In cluster analysis, squared distances can be used to strengthen the effect of longer distances.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/euclidean-distance] Squared Euclidean distance does not form a metric space, as it does not satisfy the triangle inequality.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/euclidean-distance] However it is a smooth, strictly convex function of the two points, unlike the distance, which is non-smooth (near pairs of equal points) and convex but not strictly convex.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/euclidean-distance] The squared distance is thus preferred in optimization theory, since it allows convex analysis to be used.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/euclidean-distance] Since squaring is a monotonic function of non-negative values, minimizing squared distance is equivalent to minimizing the Euclidean distance, so the optimization problem is equivalent in terms of either, but easier to solve using squared distance.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/euclidean-distance] The collection of all squared distances between pairs of points from a finite set may be stored in a Euclidean distance matrix, and is used in this form in distance geometry.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/euclidean-distance] In more advanced areas of mathematics, when viewing Euclidean space as a vector space, its distance is associated with a norm called the Euclidean norm, defined as the distance of each vector from the origin.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/euclidean-distance] One of the important properties of this norm, relative to other norms, is that it remains unchanged under arbitrary rotations of space around the origin.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/euclidean-distance] By Dvoretzky's theorem, every finite-dimensional normed vector space has a high-dimensional subspace on which the norm is approximately Euclidean; the Euclidean norm is the only norm with this property.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/euclidean-distance] It can be extended to infinite-dimensional vector spaces as the *L*2 norm or *L*2 distance.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/euclidean-distance] The Euclidean distance gives Euclidean space the structure of a topological space, the Euclidean topology, with the open balls (subsets of points at less than a given distance from a given point) as its neighborhoods.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/euclidean-distance] For points on surfaces in three dimensions, the Euclidean distance should be distinguished from the geodesic distance, the length of a shortest curve that belongs to the surface.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/euclidean-distance] Euclidean distance is the distance in Euclidean space.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/euclidean-distance] Both concepts are named after ancient Greek mathematician Euclid, whose *Elements* became a standard textbook in geometry for many centuries.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/euclidean-distance] But the notion of a distance, as a number defined from two points, does not actually appear in Euclid's *Elements*.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/euclidean-distance] Instead, Euclid approaches this concept implicitly, through the congruence of line segments, through the comparison of lengths of line segments, and through the concept of proportionality.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/euclidean-distance] The Pythagorean theorem is also ancient, but it could only take its central role in the measurement of distances after the invention of Cartesian coordinates by René Descartes in 1637.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/euclidean-distance] The distance formula itself was first published in 1731 by Alexis Clairaut.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/euclidean-distance] Because of this formula, Euclidean distance is also sometimes called Pythagorean distance.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/euclidean-distance] The definition of the Euclidean norm and Euclidean distance for geometries of more than three dimensions also first appeared in the 19th century, in the work of Augustin-Louis Cauchy.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/k-d-tree] In computer science, a ***k*-d tree** (short for *k-dimensional tree*) is a space-partitioning data structure for organizing points in a *k*-dimensional space.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/k-d-tree] K-dimensional is that which concerns exactly k orthogonal axes or a space of any number of dimensions.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/k-d-tree] The *k*-d tree is a binary tree in which *every* node is a *k*-dimensional point.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/k-d-tree] Every non-leaf node can be thought of as implicitly generating a splitting hyperplane that divides the space into two parts, known as half-spaces.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/k-d-tree] Points to the left of this hyperplane are represented by the left subtree of that node and points to the right of the hyperplane are represented by the right subtree.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/k-d-tree] The hyperplane direction is chosen in the following way: every node in the tree is associated with one of the *k* dimensions, with the hyperplane perpendicular to that dimension's axis.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/k-d-tree] So, for example, if for a particular split the "x" axis is chosen, all points in the subtree with a smaller "x" value than the node will appear in the left subtree and all points with a larger "x" value will be in the right subtree.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/k-d-tree] In such a case, the hyperplane would be set by the x value of the point, and its normal would be the unit x-axis.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/k-d-tree] Since there are many possible ways to choose axis-aligned splitting planes, there are many different ways to construct *k*-d trees.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/k-d-tree] This method leads to a balanced *k*-d tree, in which each leaf node is approximately the same distance from the root.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/k-d-tree] However, balanced trees are not necessarily optimal for all applications.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/k-d-tree] Note that it is not *required* to select the median point.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/k-d-tree] In the case where median points are not selected, there is no guarantee that the tree will be balanced.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/k-d-tree] To avoid coding a complex $O(n)$ median-finding algorithm or using an $O(n\log(n))$ sort such as heapsort or mergesort to sort all *n* points, a popular practice is to sort a *fixed* number of *randomly* *selected* points, and use the median of those points to serve as the splitting plane.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/k-d-tree] In practice, this technique often results in nicely balanced trees.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/k-d-tree] Given a list of *n* points, the following algorithm uses a median-finding sort to construct a balanced *k*-d tree containing those points.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/k-d-tree] It is common that points "after" the median include only the ones that are strictly greater than the median in the current dimension.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/k-d-tree] For points that lie on the median in the current dimension, it is possible to define a function that compares them in all dimensions.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/k-d-tree] In some cases, it is acceptable to let points equal to the median lie on one side of the median, for example, by splitting the points into a "lesser than" subset and a "greater than or equal to" subset.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/k-d-tree] This algorithm creates the invariant that for any node, all the nodes in the left subtree are on one side of a splitting plane, and all the nodes in the right subtree are on the other side.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/k-d-tree] Points that lie on the splitting plane may appear on either side.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/k-d-tree] The splitting plane of a node goes through the point associated with that node (referred to in the code as *node.location*).
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/k-d-tree] Alternative algorithms for building a balanced *k*-d tree presort the data prior to building the tree.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/k-d-tree] Then, they maintain the order of the presort during tree construction and hence eliminate the costly step of finding the median at each level of subdivision.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/k-d-tree] Two such algorithms build a balanced *k*-d tree to sort triangles in order to improve the execution time of ray tracing for three-dimensional computer graphics.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/k-d-tree] These algorithms presort *n* triangles prior to building the *k*-d tree, then build the tree in $O(n\log n)$ time in the best case.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/k-d-tree] An algorithm that builds a balanced *k*-d tree to sort points has a worst-case complexity of $O(kn\log(n))$ .
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/k-d-tree] This algorithm presorts *n* points in each of *k* dimensions using an $O(n\log(n))$ sort such as Heapsort or Mergesort prior to building the tree.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/k-d-tree] It then maintains the order of these *k* presorts during tree construction and thereby avoids finding the median at each level of subdivision.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/k-d-tree] One adds a new point to a *k*-d tree in the same way as one adds an element to any other search tree.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/k-d-tree] First, traverse the tree, starting from the root and moving to either the left or the right child depending on whether the point to be inserted is on the "left" or "right" side of the splitting plane.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/k-d-tree] Once you get to the node under which the child should be located, add the new point as either the left or right child of the leaf node, again depending on which side of the node's splitting plane contains the new node.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/k-d-tree] Adding points in this manner can cause the tree to become unbalanced, leading to decreased tree performance.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/k-d-tree] The rate of tree performance degradation is dependent upon the spatial distribution of tree points being added, and the number of points added in relation to the tree size.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/k-d-tree] If a tree becomes too unbalanced, it may need to be re-balanced to restore the performance of queries that rely on the tree balancing, such as nearest neighbour searching.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/k-d-tree] To remove a point from an existing *k*-d tree without breaking the invariant, the easiest way is to form the set of all nodes and leaves from the children of the target node and recreate that part of the tree.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/k-d-tree] Another approach is to find a replacement for the point removed.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/k-d-tree] First, find the node R that contains the point to be removed.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/k-d-tree] For the base case, where R is a leaf node, no replacement is required.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/k-d-tree] For the general case, find a replacement point, say p , from the subtree rooted at R .
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/k-d-tree] For finding a replacement point, if R discriminates on x (say) and R has a right child, find the point with the minimum x value from the subtree rooted at the right child.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/k-d-tree] Otherwise, find the point with the maximum x value from the subtree rooted at the left child.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/k-d-tree] Balancing a *k*-d tree requires care because *k*-d trees are sorted in multiple dimensions, so the tree-rotation technique cannot be used to balance them as this may break the invariant.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/k-d-tree] Several variants of balanced *k*-d trees exist.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/k-d-tree] They include divided *k*-d tree, pseudo *k*-d tree, K-D-B-tree, hB-tree and Bkd-tree.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/k-d-tree] Many of these variants are adaptive k-d trees.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/k-d-tree] The nearest neighbour search (NN) algorithm aims to find the point in the tree that is nearest to a given input point.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/k-d-tree] This search can be done efficiently by using the tree properties to quickly eliminate large portions of the search space.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/k-d-tree] Once the algorithm reaches a leaf node, it checks the node point and if the distance is better than the "current best", that node point is saved as the "current best".
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/k-d-tree] The algorithm checks whether there could be any points on the other side of the splitting plane that are closer to the search point than the current best.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/k-d-tree] In concept, this is done by intersecting the splitting hyperplane with a hypersphere around the search point that has a radius equal to the current nearest distance.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/k-d-tree] Since the hyperplanes are all axis-aligned this is implemented as a simple comparison to see whether the distance between the splitting coordinate of the search point and current node is less than the distance (overall coordinates) from the search point to the current best.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/k-d-tree] If the hypersphere doesn't intersect the splitting plane, then the algorithm continues walking up the tree, and the entire branch on the other side of that node is eliminated.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/k-d-tree] When the algorithm finishes this process for the root node, then the search is complete.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/k-d-tree] Generally the algorithm uses squared distances for comparison to avoid computing square roots.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/k-d-tree] Additionally, it can save computation by holding the squared current best distance in a variable for comparison.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/k-d-tree] The algorithm can be extended in several ways by simple modifications.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/k-d-tree] It can provide the *k* nearest neighbours to a point by maintaining *k* current bests instead of just one.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/k-d-tree] A branch is only eliminated when *k* points have been found and the branch cannot have points closer than any of the *k* current bests.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/k-d-tree] It can also be converted to an approximation algorithm to run faster.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/k-d-tree] For example, approximate nearest neighbour searching can be achieved by simply setting an upper bound on the number of points to examine in the tree or by interrupting the search process based upon a real time clock (which may be more appropriate in hardware implementations).
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/k-d-tree] The nearest neighbour for points that are already in the tree can be achieved by not updating the refinement for nodes that give zero distance.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/k-d-tree] As a result, this has the downside of discarding points that are not unique but are co-located with the original search point.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/k-d-tree] Approximate nearest neighbour is useful in real-time applications such as robotics due to the significant speed increase gained by not searching for the best point exhaustively.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/k-d-tree] One of its implementations is best-bin-first search.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/k-d-tree] A range search searches for ranges of parameters.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/k-d-tree] For example, if a tree is storing values corresponding to income and age, then a range search might be something like looking for all members of the tree which have an age between 20 and 50 years and an income between 50,000 and 80,000.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/k-d-tree] Since k-d trees divide the range of a domain in half at each level of the tree, they are useful for performing range searches.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/k-d-tree] Analyses of binary search trees has found that the worst case time for range search in a *k*-dimensional *k*-d tree containing *n* nodes is given by the following equation.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/k-d-tree] In low-dimensional spaces, the nearest point is an $O(\log(n))$ operation on average, in the case of randomly distributed points, although analysis in general is tricky.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/k-d-tree] In high-dimensional spaces, the curse of dimensionality causes the algorithm to need to visit many more branches than in lower-dimensional spaces.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/k-d-tree] In particular, when the number of points is only slightly higher than the number of dimensions, the algorithm is only slightly better than a linear search of all of the points.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/k-d-tree] As a general rule, if the dimensionality is *k*, the number of points in the data, *n*, should be $n\gg 2^{k}$ .
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/k-d-tree] Otherwise, when *k*-d trees are used with high-dimensional data, most of the points in the tree will be evaluated and the efficiency is no better than exhaustive search, and, if a good-enough fast answer is required, approximate nearest-neighbour methods should be used instead.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/k-d-tree] (In the worst case, consider a cloud of points distributed on the surface of a sphere centered at the origin.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/k-d-tree] This may result in a nearest neighbor search failing to return a nearest neighbor, which means no points are within this maximum distance from the query point.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/k-d-tree] Instead of points, a *k*-d tree can also contain rectangles or hyperrectangles.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/k-d-tree] Thus range search becomes the problem of returning all rectangles intersecting the search rectangle.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/k-d-tree] The tree is constructed the usual way with all the rectangles at the leaves.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/k-d-tree] In an orthogonal range search, the *opposite* coordinate is used when comparing against the median.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/k-d-tree] For example, if the current level is split along xhigh, we check the xlow coordinate of the search rectangle.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/k-d-tree] If the median is less than the xlow coordinate of the search rectangle, then no rectangle in the left branch can ever intersect with the search rectangle and so can be pruned.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/k-d-tree] Otherwise both branches should be traversed.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/k-d-tree] See also interval tree, which is a 1-dimensional special case.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/k-d-tree] It is also possible to define a *k*-d tree with points stored solely in leaves.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/k-d-tree] This form of *k*-d tree allows a variety of split mechanics other than the standard median split.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/k-d-tree] The midpoint splitting rule selects on the middle of the longest axis of the space being searched, regardless of the distribution of points.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/k-d-tree] This guarantees that the aspect ratio will be at most 2:1, but the depth is dependent on the distribution of points.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/k-d-tree] A variation, called sliding-midpoint, only splits on the middle if there are points on both sides of the split.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/k-d-tree] Otherwise, it splits on point nearest to the middle.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/k-d-tree] Maneewongvatana and Mount show that this offers "good enough" performance on common data sets.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/k-d-tree] Using sliding-midpoint, an approximate nearest neighbour query can be answered in $O\left({\tfrac {1}{{\epsilon \ }^{d}}}\log n\right)$ .
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/k-d-tree] Approximate range counting can be answered in $O\left(\log n+{\left({\tfrac {1}{\epsilon \ }}\right)}^{d}\right)$ with this method.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/sweep-line-algorithm] In computational geometry, a **sweep line algorithm** or **plane sweep algorithm** is an algorithmic paradigm that uses a conceptual *sweep line* or *sweep surface* to solve various problems in Euclidean space.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/sweep-line-algorithm] It is one of the critical techniques in computational geometry.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/sweep-line-algorithm] The idea behind algorithms of this type is to imagine that a line (often a vertical line) is swept or moved across the plane, stopping at some points.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/sweep-line-algorithm] Geometric operations are restricted to geometric objects that either intersect or are in the immediate vicinity of the sweep line whenever it stops, and the complete solution is available once the line has passed over all objects.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/sweep-line-algorithm] An application of the approach had led to a breakthrough in the computational complexity of geometric algorithms when Shamos and Hoey presented algorithms for line segment intersection in the plane in 1976.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/sweep-line-algorithm] In particular, they described how a combination of the scanline approach with efficient data structures (self-balancing binary search trees) makes it possible to detect whether there are intersections among N segments in the plane in time complexity of O(*N* log *N*).
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/sweep-line-algorithm] The closely related Bentley–Ottmann algorithm uses a sweep line technique to report all K intersections among any N segments in the plane in time complexity of O((*N* + *K*) log *N*) and space complexity of O(*N*).
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/sweep-line-algorithm] Since then, this approach has been used to design efficient algorithms for a number of problems in computational geometry, such as the construction of the Voronoi diagram (Fortune's algorithm) and the Delaunay triangulation or boolean operations on polygons.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/sweep-line-algorithm] Topological sweeping is a form of plane sweep with a simple ordering of processing points, which avoids the necessity of completely sorting the points; it allows some sweep line algorithms to be performed more efficiently.
[src:closest-pair-algorithm/sweep-line-algorithm] The sweeping approach may be generalised to higher dimensions.
